text: hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new milo album
a toothpaste suburb milo is a rapper
whose roots lay back in wisconsin and
this is his first full-length commercial
project which is kind of hard to think
because i've been following this guy's
music now for a handful of years
and it's been kind of a long somewhat
windy and rocky road to get to this
point back in 2010 in wisconsin milo was
yet to really go solo and was still
making music in the rap project namdae
rap but in 2011 that's when i heard of
him he dropped his i wish my brother rob
was here mixtape which i totally loved
then he put out an ep rapping over a
bunch of baths instrumentals that i
wasn't that crazy about but the
following year is when he really came
together not only prolifically but
artistically putting out music under the
scallops hotel name
dropping music with hellfire club
teaming up with open mic eagle and bus
driver and no can do that was really
coming out in a big way and then he was
coming out with great solo projects that
fans and critics alike seem to be
praising like cavalcade and his things
that happen tonight things that happen
at day eps you may remember those are my
favorite eps of last year milo's music
was very slowly and very organically
gaining a passionate audience and
impressing the ears of child literacy
advocates and ex-porn stars alike and
the fact that milo would be able to
appeal to such a wide audience is not
really surprising considering that in
his music he comes off very clever funny
humble likable smart and deviously nerdy
it's funny to think of how many mcs are
out there right now
marketing themselves and pimping
themselves out as being different
breaking the mold in hip-hop i'm not
your typical rapper but to me milo right
now really is that quintessential
anti-rapper and he could be dethroned
one day but there aren't many mc's in my
opinion that as hard are working against
the self-centeredness and the brags and
the materialism the aggression and the
attitude and the few people who could
compete with him on that level he's
already collaborating with them on this
record and with these collaborators
instead of hip-hop stereotypes milo
offers
vulnerability abstractions philosophy an
endless gauntlet of references to sci-fi
rpgs and pop culture and a wrap flow
that borders on calming spoken word and
a lyrical style that seems to emphasize
the idea of just stream of consciousness
free subject association rather than a
clear theme or concept or storyline
sonically the aesthetic of this project
isn't really that too far off from what
milo was doing on his things that
happened eps to produce he brings on
igloo ghost tastes nothing gray hat and
of course once again riley lake and
together they assemble a group of
instrumentals that not only are very
ethereal and are very lush and colorful
but have a bit of a west coast flavor to
them too
like these guys are really pulling from
flying lotus and that whole brain feeder
camp maybe a little bit of james blake
too there are lots of punchy off-kilter
beats very vibrant synthesizers from
rich cords to very bubbly bleeps and
bloops there are tons of effects laid
into these instrumentals too i think by
the end of this record the instrumental
tone of this album does get a little
old it does get a little stale it's not
like there's a ton of variety across
these beats even the ones that hit
hardest are fairly gentle and aren't
really that poppy nearly every beat here
has kind of a relaxed vibe to it but
some songs are softer more subtle more
beautiful more ethereal and others are a
little more dry and tangible but in
terms of the lyrics it's a little bit
more difficult to come together with a
summation even though this record does
start off with a really clear idea the
opening track here starts off with a bit
of a story milo talking about moving
into his first apartment his first
apartment on the west coast his first
apartment in general i'm not totally
sure but he's talking about the life
he's leading at this point rusty dollar
store pots and pans living broke
borrowing a preamp from open mic eagle
really tiny insignificant mundane things
that in isolation would be totally
uninteresting but milo finds a way to
pull them together into a pretty good
song there are even some funny lines
that turn up one where he says that he
couldn't afford cover art from folk
artist clementine hunter there is a
little mantra that milo repeats a few
times at the end of the track too but it
doesn't really pull the song together
but how could this little lyrical
repetition pull this entire track
together it's not like a package it's
not a box it's a bunch of little
trinkets just all strewn about toward
the middle point of the instrumental
thing seemed to go really ethereal for a
moment milo starts with whipping out
these lyrics that seem to deal in
violence and abuse toward black people
talking about media lies a lot of stuff
that seems to be pretty relevant given
the recent events in ferguson missouri
it's a really heartfelt moment in the
song and for sure an authentic
expression of what milo feels on this
topic however
this moment in the track doesn't really
have much more weight than any other
moment in the track or any other moment
on this record because it's mentioned
it's approached with the same brevity
that nearly everything else on this
album is i think the mental state of
this record can be boiled down to a
single line in milo's lyrics one where
he says he was going to learn the
keyboard and write several ballads but
instead at a cookout he got lost in the
tater salad listening to a toothpaste
suburb is a lot like
reading a series of diary entries and
and bits of poetry from someone who has
a severe inability to focus on anything
and milo's inability or refusal to focus
is only emphasized by this record's lack
of hooks and
milo's sort of monotonous flow and voice
and when milo does try to write hooks
they can be a little hit or miss some i
like weak and e
great clumps of sky but others like the
song argyle socks which features one of
the harder beats on the record they're a
bunch of harp samples bus drivers going
wild on the hook this instrumental is
a freaking mess but to mention bus
driver he dropped an album recently i
loved that record and a lot like milo he
seems to
avoid just delivering a simple
straightforward song structure and when
he does he really does something weird
and progressive in the process he really
does it on his own terms milo also tries
to opt out of traditional structures but
he offers very little in their place for
sure a lot of these beats instrumentals
tracks are
linear in structure we're sort of
getting this one spot and then in the
middle there's a significant change goes
into something completely different but
a lot of these changes a lot of this
beauty a lot of what makes these songs
intriguing from beginning to end has
much more to do with the instrumentals
than it does with milo almost every
single line on this project no matter
how good it is is just dust floating in
milo's breath because each line
builds off of and builds up to
nothing it's like i'm listening to a
melancholy punchline wrapper with way
too many inside jokes and whose sense of
humor ranges from dry to incredibly
immature the beginning of a toothpaste
suburb is really great i think this
album kicks off well and maybe that's
partially because the fact that milo
doesn't offer much lyrical guidance
through these songs it's it's yet to set
in but it's the back end of this album
that i think ends up
really lacking especially starting with
the song just us i mean you know i i
can't step in and say how you should or
should not tribute a friend but to me
this revision of this song doesn't
really live up to the original in any
way shape or form however this is one of
the few songs that actually focuses on a
topic and delivers some really personal
accounts of a very significant moment in
milo's life and that alone makes this
track so much more enjoyable than many
of the other songs in the track list
here the end of this record doesn't feel
any more significant than the beginning
of this record it's just all really so
uneventful in my opinion and it's not
that milo is a one-dimensional rapper or
one-dimensional artist it's just that i
think he goes about
addressing all of these dimensions so
haphazardly and so quickly and so
effortlessly and so insignificantly that
at the end of the day it all sounds like
it's just one dimension there's some
great beats on this record a lot of the
rhymes are endearing milo still has a
personality that i think is enjoyable in
music but a lot of the things that at
the start of his career made him kind of
stand out and made him different on this
project are now starting to limit him a
little bit i think i'm feeling a strong
five to a light six on this lp tran
position if you've given this record a
listen what did you think of it did you
love it did you hate it why what do you
think i should review next and that's it
anthony fantano a toothpaste suburb
forever
